                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.11/828: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-06-12T19:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 12, 1928—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 12—10:44 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>457. Your telegram number 184, June 8, 8 [<hi rend="italic">5</hi>] p.m. I
                    strongly advise against making any reply to the Nanking Foreign Office note of
                    June 2nd,<note n="78" xml:id="d180fn78">See telegram No. 427, June 5, from the
                        Minister in China, <ref target="#pg_236">p. 236</ref>.</note> which, by
                    sufficiently clear implication, acquiesces in the necessity of our armed forces
                    at this date for the safeguarding of our nationals there under the prevailing
                    conditions of insecurity and uncertainty. Any attempt to set forth the point
                    more explicitly would seem certain to elicit from the new Nanking Minister for
                    Foreign Affairs, C. T. Wang, rejoinder confusing the whole issue and seeking to
                    put us in the wrong.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
